θεὸν τῆς ἀλνθείας</span>, but there is no doubt as to the meaning. The
Scripture was read, and listening to it was regarded as hearing the
voice of God, whose words of truth were read. Then followed the sermon
or exhortation; comp. <span id="x.iii-p169.2"></span>Justin, <span
id="x.iii-p169.3"></span>First Apology, chap. lxvii. (vol. i. p. 186).
That lessons from some at least of the New Testament were included at
the date of this homily, seems quite certain; comp. the references to
the New Testament in chaps. ii., iii., iv., and elsewhere. It is here
implied that this homily was written and “read.”  

<span id="fn_4003"></span>[523:4004](0070476.htm#fr_4003.md) <span
id="x.iii-p169.5"></span>

<span id="x.iii-p170"></span> The word <span class="Greek"><span
id="x.iii-p170.1"></span>ἒντευζις</span>, here used, means intercession,
or supplication, to God (comp. [1 Tim. ii.
1](../../../bib/kjv/ti1002.htm#001.md)<span id="x.iii-p170.2"></span>, iv.
5) in early Christian literature: but the classical sense is “entreaty:”
so in the opening sentence of <span id="x.iii-p170.3"></span>Justin,
<span id="x.iii-p170.4"></span>First Apology (vol. i. p. 163, where it
is rendered “petition”).  

<span id="fn_4004"></span>[523:4005](0070476.htm#fr_4004.md) <span
id="x.iii-p170.5"></span>

<span id="x.iii-p171"></span> <span id="x.iii-p171.1"></span>Lightfoot,
with Syriac and most editors, reads <span class="Greek"><span
id="x.iii-p171.2"></span>σκοπόν</span>; but C has <span
class="Greek"><span id="x.iii-p171.3"></span>κόπον</span>, so <span
id="x.iii-p171.4"></span>Bryennios.  

<span id="fn_4005"></span>[523:4006](0070476.htm#fr_4005.md) <span
id="x.iii-p171.5"></span>

<span id="x.iii-p172"></span> C had originally <span class="Greek"><span
id="x.iii-p172.1"></span>φιλοσοφει̑ν</span> (accepted by <span
id="x.iii-p172.2"></span>Hilgenfeld), but was corrected to <span
class="Greek"><span id="x.iii-p172.3"></span>φιλοπονει̑ν</span>. The
latter is confirmed by the Syriac, and now generally accepted, though
<span id="x.iii-p172.4"></span>Hilgenfeld uses the other reading to
support his view that <span id="x.iii-p172.5"></span>Clement of
Alexandria was the author.  

<span id="fn_4006"></span>[523:4007](0070476.htm#fr_4006.md) <span
id="x.iii-p172.6"></span>

<span id="x.iii-p173"></span> [Eph. iv.
18](../../../bib/kjv/eph004.htm#018.md)<span id="x.iii-p173.1"></span>.  

<span id="fn_4007"></span>[523:4008](0070476.htm#fr_4007.md) <span
id="x.iii-p173.2"></span>

<span id="x.iii-p174"></span> C inserts <span class="Greek"><span
id="x.iii-p174.1"></span>τούτω</span>; so <span
id="x.iii-p174.2"></span>Bryennios, <span
id="x.iii-p174.3"></span>Hilgenfeld, and others. <span
id="x.iii-p174.4"></span>Lightfoot omits, with Syriac. The punctuation
above given is that of <span id="x.iii-p174.5"></span>Bryennios and
<span id="x.iii-p174.6"></span>Lightfoot. <span
id="x.iii-p174.7"></span>Hilgenfeld joins this clause with what
precedes.  

<span id="fn_4008"></span>[523:4009](0070476.htm#fr_4008.md) <span
id="x.iii-p175.1"></span>

<span id="x.iii-p176"></span> <span class="Greek"><span
id="x.iii-p176.1"></span>πει̑ραν ἀθλου̑μεν</span>; the construction is
classical, and the figure common in all Greek literature.  

<span id="fn_4009"></span>[523:4010](0070476.htm#fr_4009.md) <span
id="x.iii-p176.2"></span>

<span id="x.iii-p177"></span> The verbs here are aorists, and have been
rendered by the English past tense; the present participle (<span
class="Greek"><span id="x.iii-p177.1"></span>μὴ ὂν δίκαιον</span>)
describing the character of the “spirit” must, according to English
usage, conform to the main verbs. <span
id="x.iii-p177.2"></span>Lightfoot says, “The aorist here has its common
<span id="x.iii-p177.3"></span>gnomic sense;” and he therefore
interprets the passage as a general statement: “Sordid motives bring
their own punishment in a judicial blindness.” But this gnomic sense of
the aorist is not common. C reads <span class="Greek"><span
id="x.iii-p177.4"></span>δεσμός</span>, which yields this sense: “and a
chain weighed <span id="x.iii-p177.5"></span>upon him.” <span
id="x.iii-p177.6"></span>Hilgenfeld refers the passage to those
Christians who suffered persecution for other causes than those of
righteousness. <span id="x.iii-p177.7"></span>Harnack thinks the author
has in mind Satan, as the prince of avarice, and regards him as already
loaded with chains. If the aorist is taken in its usual sense, this is
the preferable explanation; but the meaning is obscure.  

<span id="fn_4010"></span>[523:4011](0070476.htm#fr_4010.md) <span
id="x.iii-p178.1"></span>

<span id="x.iii-p179"></span> [1 Tim. i.
17](../../../bib/kjv/ti1001.htm#017.md)<span id="x.iii-p179.1"></span>.  

<span id="fn_4011"></span>[523:4012](0070476.htm#fr_4011.md) <span
id="x.iii-p179.2"></span>

<span id="x.iii-p180"></span> [Acts iii.
15](../../../bib/kjv/act003.htm#015.md)<span id="x.iii-p180.1"></span>, v.
31; comp. [Heb. ii. 10](../../../bib/kjv/heb002.htm#010.md)<span
id="x.iii-p180.2"></span>.  

<span id="fn_4012"></span>[523:4013](0070476.htm#fr_4012.md) <span
id="x.iii-p180.3"></span>

<span id="x.iii-p181"></span> The doxology is interesting, as indicating
the early custom of thus closing a homily. The practice, fitting in
itself, naturally followed the examples in the Epistles.  

